data.content:
Here are the idiomatic MSTest replacements:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));  // no built-in predicate assert
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count());
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count())` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, element)`
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` â€” same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` â€” any order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`

The `All(u => u.IsActive)` predicate check has no direct `CollectionAssert` equivalent, so `Assert.IsTrue` is still the pragmatic choice there. Alternatively, you could loop and assert each item individually for better failure messages.
